Notes:
Hi, my name is Brett Logan and I sing BARI with The Blenders. I joined the choir in Feb 1997 and my birthday is on the 21st of August. I am a Baritone Section Leader in the chorus which means I Musical leader of the Baritone voices. I am also a Assistant MD which means I Assists in the duties of Music Director.

I moved to the Gold Coast from Sydney in 2003 after marrying my NZ born wife Reagan who I met while travelling. I wanted to make some local friends and so I came along to the rehearsal of the Gold Coast City Choir. However I got the night wrong and joined the Blenders as well. I have been unable to escape ever since. 

My daughter Raine was born 1995, daughter India in 1997, and son Gray in 1999

I first joined the Blenders under the Direction of Jim Catt and was immediately moved to the front row so the chorus could capitalize on my rugged good looks. By 1998 I was singing with the quartet Up 4 Grabs and was club treasurer where I presided over the introduction of credit cards.

My father died in 1999 a few weeks after my son Gray's birth and I had to decline the role of treasurer to take more responsibility in the family business. The Logan family owns and operates The Tweed Heads Vegas Motel.

The quartet Up for Grabs survived though and I spent the next 5 years taking enormous pleasure singing Lead, with Martin Neary on Bass, Steve Griffin on Bari and Chris Gray on Tenor. Up for Grabs was the first (and only) Blenders quartet to put on a full length dinner show. There are still many who remember the rubber chickens and the innovation of hand held microphones (gasp). Our best National result was a top ten place at Brisbane in 1999.

I have served on the club Executive on numerous occasions since and as MusicVP with the directors Bernie Cureton, Rose McGee, Aaron Griffin and Andrew Howson. I have been both a Lead and a Tenor section leader on the music team.

I created this website sometime near the millenial year 2000. Unfortunately I had to learn php, mysql and html to do it so the underlying code in the older sections is rather rough. I hosted both the public and members area code on a server in my living room for many years.

Sometime around 2001 I was also singing with Good News, the Gospel quartet with Brian Denton, Keith Lay, and David Gamble.

I joined the Crossroads quartet as Tenor in 2003, with Derek Cosburn on Lead, Avon Philips on Bass and Andrew Howson on Bari. At the time I was MusicVP and filling in as Tenor Section leader with the chorus till a replacement could be found. We achieved a regional Gold medal that year as well as 2004 and 2005. At the 2003 National convention in Perth Crossroads acheived a National Silver medal and later a Bronze on the Gold Coast in 2005.

2007 was the first year I didn't sing in Quartet at Nationals, however my lust for harmony was soon being assuaged by singing with the mixed acappella group Cloud 8. Charlie, Johnny, Gunther and me with ladies Rose, Rina, Leigh and Sally. I also scaled Mt Everest and broke the world land speed record in the Mohave. (Just seeing if you are really reading all this) http://cloud-8.org

By 2008 I was singing with five part boy band (how flattering) Vocaleez with Mike Taylor, Aaron Griffin, Chris Hope and Mitch Bruger. http://vocaleez.com

In 2009 I was back into a BBS quartet. Forte ranked 6th place at the Regionals with only a few weeks rehearsal. Except for Martin Neary who undisputedly sings Bass, Pete Gray, Mitch Bruger and I take turns at Bari, Lead and Tenor.

I was responsible for the start of the Blenders open mic. nights in 2008 with the Beatles themed night at the hall and later a Xmas show. In 2009 I convened the Voices in the Night acappella show as well as the Spirit of Xmas show at the German Club.

Late 2009 also saw me initiate the SingFest acappella festival as convener due to be combined with the Sunshine Regional Convention in May 2010. http://www.SingFest.com.au

In 2010 I took up a post as Director of Voice Weavers aCappella Choir, a 30 voice ensemble singing choral arrangements of pop music with a bit contemporary acappella, world music and traditional choral thrown in for variety.

I have sung on TV with The Blenders at X-Factor, Battle of the Choirs, and recently, Australia's Got Talent. I have traveled to Anaheim and Denver sung on the International stage and to Armidale with the chorus.

I am currently the Blenders representative on the Sunshine Region as Vice Chairman. I sing with ensembles Forte, Vocaleez, and am MD of Voice Weavers Choir in Coolangatta. I also play Bass guitar in the band Pepper Spray which is comprised entirely of Logans. I have 6 chorus Gold Medals and 2 Silver, 2 Pan Pacific medals, 3 Regional Gold medals and a National Silver and National Bronze Quartet medals and I proudly wear them all at our National Barbershop Conventions.
